            <article data-uuid="c0636072c4d148f2985c707bff9436b6">
                <h4 data-uuid="08b8fc39021e45b9988d768c87afbfa2">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="05c9eb37c5734df5a7f6f824466b7065">The United States led postwar rebuilding after World War II left much of Europe and Asia devastated.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="55480d9c4ad749b1b7da7dd590b980eb">After the War</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="074cbfbe8ca24c1ebaea4d19ffcd7a1e"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="c969d3a5f9744b6d91e38250e23ad838">After six years, World War II was finally over. More than 50 million people had been killed—more than half of them civilians. National economies in Europe and Asia were devastated, and millions of people were left without food, water, or shelter. Since the war had been fought far from American soil, the United States escaped this level of destruction. As the strongest power left in the world, much of the responsibility for postwar rebuilding fell to the United States, which sent billions of dollars to its European allies and even its defeated enemies.<br />
        </p>
